      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/grandyle_village_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The island was first a Seneca hunting preserve before the 1815 treaty ceded it to New York State.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        20
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/grandyle_village_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "French explorers met the Neutral Nation in the 1600s; by 1651 the Senecas claimed the island as Ga‑we‑not, \"Great Island.\"",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        18
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/grandyle_village_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The 1825 Erie Canal opened timber trade, drawing logging companies like the East Boston Company to Whitehaven on Grand Island.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/grandyle_village_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Grandyle Village’s name reflects its location on Grand Island’s southwestern shore along the Niagara River.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grandyle_Village%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "In the 1950s, Interstate 190 linked Grandyle Village to Buffalo, turning it into a bedroom community for city workers.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
